  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Having €10,000 Clearly Accessible</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Ireland requires €10,000 immediately available—not spread across accounts, not locked in investments. Show a single bank statement with €10,000+ available. If funds are recently deposited, be prepared to explain the source.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting to Register with GNIB/IRP</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must register with immigration within 90 days of arrival. In Dublin, appointments are difficult to get—book immediately after arriving. Missing this deadline can jeopardize your immigration status.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Public Healthcare Access</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Students cannot access free HSE (public) healthcare until establishing "habitual residence" (1+ year). You must have private insurance from day one. Don't assume you can use public services like in Italy or UK.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Dublin Costs</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dublin is one of Europe's most expensive cities. Budget €1,300-2,000/month for living costs. Consider Cork, Galway, or Limerick for lower costs with excellent universities and quality of life.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing Stamp 1G Opportunity</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After completing a Level 8+ degree, apply for Stamp 1G immediately—it's a 2-year work permission that's extremely valuable. Many students don't realize they need to apply proactively; it's not automatic.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Ireland -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Ireland</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Ireland has both public (HSE) and private healthcare systems. As an international student, you'll primarily use private healthcare through your insurance, as public access is limited until you establish habitual residence.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Public vs. Private Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Public HSE (Limited Access)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Emergency care available to everyone</li>
          <li>• Medical card only after establishing habitual residence</li>
          <li>• GP visit without medical card: €50-65</li>
          <li>• Hospital ER without medical card: €100</li>
          <li>• Long wait times for many services</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Private Healthcare (Your Primary Option)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ Full coverage through your insurance</li>
          <li>✓ Choice of doctors and hospitals</li>
          <li>✓ Shorter wait times</li>
          <li>✓ Direct billing often available</li>
          <li>✓ Modern private hospitals</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Access Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Find a GP</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Register with a local GP (general practitioner) near your accommodation. Your insurer's app or website can help find in-network GPs. Call ahead to confirm they accept your insurance.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Using Your Insurance</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Check if your insurer offers direct billing (they pay the provider directly) or reimbursement (you pay, then claim back). Irish insurers like VHI, Laya, and Irish Life Health have extensive networks with direct billing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">University Health Services</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Most Irish universities have student health centers offering basic medical care, mental health support, and referrals. These are often free or low-cost for registered students—use them for routine issues.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Emergencies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 999 or 112 for emergencies. Hospital A&E (emergency rooms) treat everyone regardless of insurance status. You may be charged €100 if you don't have a GP referral and aren't admitted.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Pharmacies in Ireland:</strong> Pharmacists can advise on minor ailments and sell some medications without prescription. Look for the green cross sign. Some medications that require prescriptions elsewhere may be available over-the-counter in Ireland.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I access Irish public healthcare (HSE)?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not initially. Students don't qualify for free HSE services until establishing "habitual residence" (typically 1+ year). You must have private insurance from the start. After establishing residence, low-income students may qualify for a medical card.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the €10,000 requirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Ireland requires evidence of €10,000 immediately available (not annual income). Your bank statement should show €10,000 accessible. If parents are sponsoring, include their bank statement plus a sponsorship letter and relationship proof.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is Stamp 1G?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Stamp 1G is a 2-year post-study work permission for graduates of Level 8+ programs (bachelor's and above). It allows full-time work while seeking employment in your field. Apply after graduation—it's one of Europe's best post-study work options.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How much is tuition in Ireland?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          EU students may qualify for Free Fees (only ~€3,000 student contribution). Non-EU students pay €10,000-25,000/year for most programs, with medicine significantly higher (€45,000+/year). Ireland is expensive for non-EU students compared to Germany or Italy.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work while studying?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Stamp 2 allows 20 hours/week during term and 40 hours/week during holidays (June-September, December 15-January 15). Ireland's minimum wage is €12.70/hour—among Europe's highest. Working students can earn €1,000+/month.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is IELTS required?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes for most non-native English speakers. Requirements vary: typically IELTS 5.5-6.0 for undergraduate, 6.5+ for postgraduate. Some universities accept TOEFL or other tests. Native English speakers from certain countries may be exempt.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Ireland offers an English-speaking environment with strong ties to tech and pharmaceutical industries—ideal for career-focused students. The Stamp 1G post-study work visa (2 years) is one of Europe's best, and high minimum wages (€12.70/hour) make working during studies financially rewarding.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The trade-offs are cost: non-EU tuition is expensive (€10,000-25,000/year), private insurance is required (~€100/month), and Dublin living costs are high. There's no €150/year public healthcare like Italy—budget accordingly.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For students who can manage the costs, Ireland delivers: English-language education, strong career prospects, welcoming culture, and a clear path from study to employment through Stamp 1G. It's a strategic choice for those targeting tech, pharma, or finance careers in Europe.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Ireland requires private health insurance—no public healthcare access initially. Budget €80-180/month for coverage from VHI, Laya, or international insurers. The 2-year Stamp 1G post-study work visa and high wages make Ireland a strategic choice for career-focused students willing to invest in their future.
      </p>
